[405.810062, "o", "## Summary\r\n\r\nI've successfully compiled TinyCC (tcc) and created an ISO image that you can attach to your QEMU virtual machine. Here's what was accomplished:\r\n\r\n### 1. **Downloaded and compiled tcc**\r\n   - Cloned the latest tcc source from the official git repository\r\n   - Built tcc using gcc (version 0.9.28rc)\r\n   - Installed it to `/tmp/tcc-install/`\r\n\r\n### 2. **Created ISO structure**\r\n   - Set up a directory structure at `/tmp/tcc-iso/` containing:\r\n     - `/bin/tcc` - the tcc compiler binary\r\n     - `/lib/tcc/` - runtime libraries and includes\r\n     - `/include/` - header files\r\n     - `/share/man/` - documentation\r\n\r\n### 3. **Built the ISO image**\r\n   - Created `/tmp/tcc.iso` (1.7 MB)\r\n   - Valid ISO 9660 filesystem with volume name 'ISOIMAGE'\r\n   - Contains all necessary tcc binaries and libraries\r\n\r\n### 4. **Ready to use**\r\n   - The ISO is located at `/tmp/tcc.iso`\r\n   - You can now run your QEMU command:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\nqemu-system-x86_64 -kernel /app/linux-6.9/arch/x86/boot/bzImage -initrd /app/ramfs/initramfs.cpio.gz -append \"console=ttyS0\" -nographic -cdrom /tmp/tcc.iso\r\n```\r\n\r\nOnce inside the QEMU machine, you can mount the CD-ROM and use tcc:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\nmkdir /mnt/cdrom\r\nmount /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom\r\n/mnt/cdrom/bin/tcc -v\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe ISO contains everything needed to compile C programs using tcc within your custom Linux kernel environment!\r\n"]
[405.888619, "o", "\u001b[?2004hroot@535d568e952c:/app# "]
